values:
&ldquo;You&rsquo;re in charge of finger-painting with her from now on,&rdquo; said Arthur, studying his efforts critically.

&ldquo;Oh, are we adding clauses to our official co-parenting contract?&rdquo; asked Eames. &ldquo;Because I have a few.&rdquo;

&ldquo;It&rsquo;s just that you&rsquo;re clearly the artist in the family,&rdquo; sighed Arthur.

&ldquo;Darling, it&rsquo;s finger-painting,&rdquo; Eames told him, amused. &ldquo;Your paintings are fine.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Pathetic. Lucky&rsquo;s are way better.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Yeah, but Lucky&rsquo;s a prodigy.&rdquo;

&ldquo;True.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Speaking of the official co-parenting contract, can I invoke the sex clause?&rdquo;

&ldquo;You know we don&rsquo;t have an official co-parenting contract, right?&rdquo;

&ldquo;But we can have sex anyway.&rdquo;

&ldquo;I&rsquo;ll allow it,&rdquo; said Arthur.

&ldquo;They turn into butterflies,&rdquo; John told Oliver.

Oliver frowned at the caterpillar. &ldquo;&lsquo;Turn into&rsquo;?&rdquo;

John nodded.

&ldquo;Well, you make it sound like it&rsquo;s magic. It&rsquo;s not magic. How does it happen?&rdquo; demanded Oliver, confident in the steadiness of science.

&ldquo;They make a cocoon and then they turn into a butterfly,&rdquo; said John.

Oliver, perplexed, insisted on keeping the caterpillar. Oliver took copious notes on his butterfly experiment. And on the morning when John found him staring at a butterfly fluttering around the container, John said, &ldquo;What is your scientific conclusion?&rdquo;

Oliver watched the butterfly intently, then admitted, &ldquo;It was magic.&rdquo;

&ldquo;It isn&rsquo;t that I&rsquo;m nervous,&rdquo; Eames said.

&ldquo;Yes, you are,&rdquo; said Arthur, fixing Eames&rsquo;s tie.

&ldquo;She&rsquo;s not making a mistake. He&rsquo;s nice, right?&rdquo;

&ldquo;He&rsquo;s nice, Eames. He&rsquo;s lovely. He loves her. He&rsquo;ll be good to her.&rdquo;

&ldquo;It&rsquo;s just that it&rsquo;s kind of my job, right? To look out for her? I mean, when your sister asks you to give her away at her wedding, you should&hellip;be sure she&rsquo;s going to be happy.&rdquo;

&ldquo;You&rsquo;re a good brother. And you love her a lot. You&rsquo;ve already done a good job. She&rsquo;ll be happy.&rdquo;

Eames tugged Arthur into a hug. &ldquo;I just want her to find an Arthur. I want her to be <i>that</i> kind of happy.&rdquo;

&ldquo;You need an Eames for that,&rdquo; said Arthur.

&ldquo;Do you know how to build a fire?&rdquo; Matt asked, once they got to the campground.

&ldquo;Of course!&rdquo; Brem and Athena chorused, because how hard could starting a fire be?

An hour later, Matt was enjoying a beer and giving lots of advice that mainly constituted mockery.

&ldquo;You know,&rdquo; Brem huffed, &ldquo;not all of us were Boy Scouts!&rdquo;

&ldquo;Actually, I was in the Girl Scouts, remember?&rdquo; said Athena.

&ldquo;That&rsquo;s right. So why don&rsquo;t you know how to build a fire?&rdquo;

&ldquo;Because Dad and I were too busy killing a man-eating slug.&rdquo;

&ldquo;You guys have the best stories,&rdquo; said Matt fondly.

&ldquo;Sequins,&rdquo; Sherlock said flatly. &ldquo;Why are they all wearing sequins?&rdquo;

&ldquo;It&rsquo;s figure skating, Sherlock,&rdquo; John answered.

&ldquo;<i>I</i> never wore sequins,&rdquo; Sherlock sniffed.

&ldquo;Yes, but you&rsquo;re very special.&rdquo;

&ldquo;It&rsquo;s just&mdash;do they have any self-respect? Why must they glitter like a Christmas tree? The power should be in the skating, not in looking like a&hellip;something with sequins.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Disco ball?&rdquo; suggested John blandly.

&ldquo;I don&rsquo;t know. I&rsquo;m not a sequin expert.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Sherlock. Your costume had feathers.&rdquo;

&ldquo;That&rsquo;s different. That was <i>Swan Lake</i>. That made sense.&rdquo;

&ldquo;I&rsquo;m just saying: People in feathers shouldn&rsquo;t throw sequins.&rdquo;

&ldquo;And the feathers were Lestrade&rsquo;s idea,&rdquo; mumbled Sherlock.

&ldquo;Let&rsquo;s hide in there,&rdquo; Eames suggested.

&ldquo;In the barn?&rdquo;

&ldquo;Are you going to particular about where we go to save our lives?&rdquo;

Put that way&hellip;

Arthur said, &ldquo;Do not make any jokes about rolls in the hay.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Wouldn&rsquo;t dream of it.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Do not try to engage me in a roll in the hay.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Can&rsquo;t make promises about that.&rdquo; Eames stretched out in the hay on the floor.

&ldquo;You&rsquo;re going to be filthy.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Darling, come here and I&rsquo;ll show you how filthy I am. And don&rsquo;t even complain, you set that one up for me.&rdquo;

Arthur sighed and couldn&rsquo;t deny it.

&ldquo;I learned a new game at school,&rdquo; Oliver told Uncle Mycroft.

&ldquo;Sounds tedious,&rdquo; remarked Uncle Mycroft, but Oliver knew better than to believe Uncle Mycroft really meant that.

&ldquo;We have to stare at each other.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Alright.&rdquo; Uncle Mycroft looked evenly at Oliver. &ldquo;And what happens after that?&rdquo; Uncle Mycroft blinked.

&ldquo;You already lost,&rdquo; Oliver said smugly.

&ldquo;Well, that&rsquo;s not fair! I don&rsquo;t know the rules!&rdquo;

&ldquo;You can&rsquo;t blink.&rdquo;

Uncle Greg came home later and found them still having staring contests. It turned out Uncle Greg was better than both of them at it. Which made Uncle Mycroft smile a lot.

Arthur hadn&rsquo;t expected Eames&rsquo;s house to be full of people.

&ldquo;Sorry,&rdquo; Eames apologized, pulling him through the throng into a quieter room.

&ldquo;You&rsquo;re having a party,&rdquo; Arthur realized in shock.

&ldquo;Yes. I would have invited you if I&rsquo;d known you&mdash;&rdquo;

&ldquo;You have <i>friends</i>.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Yes.&rdquo;

Eames sounded amused, and Arthur felt out of his depth. &ldquo;I should go&mdash;&rdquo;

&ldquo;Stay.&rdquo;

&ldquo;I only meant to&hellip;say hello, and&mdash;&rdquo;

&ldquo;Arthur. Stay.&rdquo;

Arthur, feeling oddly shy, said, &ldquo;You don&rsquo;t have to&mdash;&rdquo;

&ldquo;Stay,&rdquo; Eames said gently. &ldquo;I want you to stay. In fact, you&rsquo;re the only one I want to stay.&rdquo;

Arthur stayed.

When Oliver was three, Sherlock set fire to the kitchen. Oliver stared at the flames; Sherlock grabbed him and rushed him out of the building.

When John arrived home to fire crews, Oliver exclaimed, &ldquo;Daddy set the house on fire!&rdquo;

&ldquo;It was a small chemical fire. They&rsquo;re making a big fuss for nothing.&rdquo;

&ldquo;It was a huge fire!&rdquo; Oliver said, holding his little arms out as far as they would go. &ldquo;Bigger than a million.&rdquo;

&ldquo;That doesn&rsquo;t even make sense, Ollie,&rdquo; said Sherlock.

&ldquo;It was so silly,&rdquo; continued Oliver, giggling now in delight. &ldquo;Because it wasn&rsquo;t even in the <i>fireplace</i>!&rdquo;

John was hanging plant life around the sitting room.

&ldquo;What are you doing?&rdquo; Sherlock asked.

John looked at him. &ldquo;It&rsquo;s Christmas.&rdquo;

Oh, thought Sherlock. Maybe it was. He didn&rsquo;t really pay attention.

&ldquo;Look.&rdquo; John gestured to the greenery over his head.

&ldquo;I see it,&rdquo; Sherlock said.

&ldquo;No, <i>look</i>,&rdquo; John said.

&ldquo;Yes, it&rsquo;s mistletoe,&rdquo; Sherlock said. &ldquo;Mildly poisonous to pets. Hemlock would have been more impressive.&rdquo;

&ldquo;You&rsquo;re supposed to kiss me,&rdquo; John said. &ldquo;Under the mistletoe.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Why?&rdquo;

&ldquo;Tradition.&rdquo;

John kissed him. Sherlock was fairly certain he was making this mistletoe thing up, but who was he to argue with a kiss?

&ldquo;What are your symptoms?&rdquo; asked Oliver, sticking his head out of the large cardboard box the new refrigerator had come in.

John realized Oliver was apparently using it as a pretend clinic. &ldquo;I have spots all over my tongue.&rdquo;

&ldquo;That&rsquo;s alarming,&rdquo; Oliver said severely. &ldquo;Let me see.&rdquo;

John stuck out his tongue.

&ldquo;No spots. You&rsquo;re imagining them. You are evidently delusional and probably a danger to yourself and others,&rdquo; was Oliver&rsquo;s cool assessment.

&ldquo;Oh,&rdquo; said John.

&ldquo;Now: do you know any dead people?&rdquo;

&ldquo;I thought this was a clinic.&rdquo;

&ldquo;It&rsquo;s a clinic that solves crimes,&rdquo; Oliver explained. &ldquo;Just like home.&rdquo;

Arthur drifted in and out of Eames&rsquo;s life. When Arthur was gone, Eames almost felt over him. Then Arthur would return, and Eames would suffer a relapse of longing adoration. When he left again, it was horrible.

&ldquo;You shouldn&rsquo;t take jobs with him,&rdquo; Yusuf said.

&ldquo;He&rsquo;s the best.&rdquo;

&ldquo;You should fuck somebody else.&rdquo;

&ldquo;I only want <i>him</i>.&rdquo;

&ldquo;You should tell him.&rdquo;

***

Eames drifted in and out of Arthur&rsquo;s life. It made Arthur twitchy, anxious, melancholy, pathetic.

&ldquo;You should tell him,&rdquo; Ariadne said.

&ldquo;But what if&mdash;&rdquo;

&ldquo;<i>Tell him</i>.&rdquo;

***

<i>There&rsquo;s something I&rsquo;ve been meaning to tell you.</i>

<i>Me, too.</i>

Eames stilled Arthur&rsquo;s hand as it reached for the gun. &ldquo;Don&rsquo;t do that.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Why not? We&rsquo;ve got a whole day of dream time left to kill,&rdquo; Arthur said.

&ldquo;Darling. Look at that lovely hill over there.&rdquo;

Arthur looked.

&ldquo;It&rsquo;s covered with <i>snow</i>.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Yeah, because you&rsquo;re obsessed with snow worlds.&rdquo;

Eames dreamed up a sled. &ldquo;Come on.&rdquo;

Arthur sighed. But Arthur also spent the entire dream afternoon sledding with Eames.

Later, he could never adequately explain what had delayed him and Eames waking from that dream. Somehow, <i>he took me sledding and I fell in love</i> didn&rsquo;t seem right to say.

Eames peered at the elaborate gingerbread version of the hotel on display in the lobby. &ldquo;I have an idea.&rdquo;

&ldquo;No,&rdquo; said Arthur. &ldquo;We&rsquo;re not stealing that.&rdquo;

&ldquo;That&rsquo;s not my idea.&rdquo;

Eames&rsquo;s idea was to make their own elaborate gingerbread houses. Arthur baked massive amounts of gingerbread, and they constructed paradoxical dreamscapes; Eames painted small masterpieces onto them. They gave them to the shops they frequented in Paris, and somehow they turned into a minor sensation on Instagram, and Cobb e-mailed with <i>Did you make gingerbread Penrose steps????</i>

&ldquo;We&rsquo;re a good team,&rdquo; Arthur told Eames.

Eames munched on gingerbread and agreed.

&ldquo;Do you know what makes me nervous about you?&rdquo; Eames asked.

Arthur pretended he wasn&rsquo;t surprised to find Eames lurking in the warehouse. &ldquo;What?&rdquo; he asked blandly.

&ldquo;Your tie is always perfect.&rdquo;

&ldquo;And that makes you nervous?&rdquo;

Eames started walking toward him, slow and predatory. Arthur had to work to hold his ground. &ldquo;It makes me feel like you don&rsquo;t like to make mistakes.&rdquo;

&ldquo;I don&rsquo;t,&rdquo; said Arthur.

Eames drew up next to him, breathed over his mouth. &ldquo;Sometimes you need the first try. You can always paint over. It&rsquo;s still something beautiful. <i>Alla prima</i>,&rdquo; murmured Eames, and kissed him.

&ldquo;You&rsquo;re terrible at this,&rdquo; said Arthur, judgily.

Eames glared at him. &ldquo;Terrible at <i>dislocating my own thumbs</i>? You&rsquo;re a freak to be good at it.&rdquo;

Arthur shrugged. &ldquo;Think of how much easier your life would have been if you could have done this every time you got arrested.&rdquo;

&ldquo;How often do you think I get arrested?&rdquo; grumbled Eames.

&ldquo;Anyway,&rdquo; said Arthur, &ldquo;this is good news.&rdquo;

&ldquo;In what way?&rdquo;

Arthur settled on his knees between Eames&rsquo;s legs and smiled wickedly.

Eames stared.

&ldquo;Now I know, when I&rsquo;ve got you handcuffed, you&rsquo;re going to stay exactly where I put you,&rdquo; purred Arthur.

&ldquo;How are you feeling?&rdquo; John asked.

&ldquo;I&rsquo;m fine,&rdquo; Sherlock retorted, even though his nose was red and raw and his eyes were glassy and he was shivering with what John was sure was a fever.

&ldquo;Uh-huh.&rdquo; John tucked a fleece blanket around Sherlock on the sofa.

&ldquo;This is stupid.&rdquo;

&ldquo;It&rsquo;s called being sick.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Well, it&rsquo;s stupid. And I&rsquo;m not actually sick.&rdquo;

&ldquo;I think you&rsquo;re a little sick. You should rest.&rdquo;

&ldquo;I don&rsquo;t need to rest,&rdquo; Sherlock denied sulkily. Then, after a moment, &ldquo;But this blanket is nice, so maybe I&rsquo;ll just&hellip;lay here and enjoy the blanket.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Good plan,&rdquo; John smiled.

&ldquo;Let&rsquo;s hang stockings,&rdquo; Eames said.

&ldquo;For what?&rdquo; asked Arthur, frowning at his paperwork.

&ldquo;For whom. Father Christmas.&rdquo;

&ldquo;No such thing.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Did the military kill your sense of magic?&rdquo;

&ldquo;No, I <i>grew up</i>. Unlike you.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Thank God. What would you ask Father Christmas for?&rdquo;

&ldquo;If he existed? A new gun.&rdquo;

Eames laughed.

&ldquo;I need one,&rdquo; said Arthur defensively.

&ldquo;I love working on Christmas with you. Let&rsquo;s do this every year. Spend every Christmas with me.&rdquo;

&ldquo;You&rsquo;re ridiculous,&rdquo; Arthur said, but his ears were pink. &ldquo;Krampus is more likely for us than Santa.&rdquo;

&ldquo;As a criminal, I take that as a compliment.&rdquo;
